{
  "doc_id": "23813",
  "text": "NAFLD/NASH in children was described for the first time in 1983 [CITATION_1] . As in adults, the diagnosis of paediatric NASH, which is the most advanced form of NAFLD, requires characteristic histological lesions, including steatosis, ballooning degeneration and lobular inflammation with or without fibrosis [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . However, the histological pattern of NAFLD in children may be either similar to, or quite disparate from, those of adults, in terms of type and distribution of lesions [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . In fact, children not only present the adult-like type 1 NAFLD, mainly characterized by steatosis in zone 3, but also two other forms: type 2 NAFLD, characterized by panacinar steatosis or accentuation of steatosis in zone 1, zero to minimal hepatocellular ballooning with or without portal inflammation and fibrosis; and 'overlap type' [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] .",
